 Here's a function called `checkPrimeInArray` that takes an array of five numbers as an argument and checks if any of them are prime numbers. If a prime number is found, it will be printed to the console.

```javascript
function checkPrimeInArray(numbers) {
  for (let i = 0; i < numbers.length; i++) {
    const num = numbers[i];
    if (isPrime(num)) {
      console.log(num);
      break; // If a prime number is found, there's no need to continue checking the array
    }
  }

  function isPrime(number) {
    if (number <= 1) return false; // Numbers less than 2 are not prime
    if (number <= 3) return true; // 2 and 3 are prime numbers

    for (let divisor = 2; divisor <= Math.sqrt(number); divisor++) {
      if (number % divisor === 0) {
        return false;
      }
    }

    return true;
  }
}
```

You can use this function by providing an array of five numbers as an argument:

```javascript
checkPrimeInArray([1, 2, 3, 4, 5]); // 2 will be printed to the console because it's a prime number
checkPrimeInArray([6, 7, 8, 9, 10]); // No prime numbers in this array, but nothing will be printed to the console as expected
```

