 Creating an automatically generated table of contents in LaTeX involves using the standard package `tableofcontents` and structuring your document with sections, subsections, and possibly higher levels of subdivisions. Here's a minimal example of a LaTeX document with multiple levels of hierarchical structure, and the `\tableofcontents` command will automatically generate a table of contents based on these levels.

```latex
\documentclass{article} % or book, report, or another suitable class for your project

% Enable 8 levels deep nested structures if needed (default is 3)
\usepackage{titlesec}
\titlespacing{\section}{0pt}{3ex plus 1ex minus .2ex}{2.3ex plus .2ex} % Customize spacing here
\titlespacing{\subsection}{0pt}{2.5ex plus 0.5ex minus 0.2ex}{1.3ex plus 0.2ex} % Customize spacing here
\titleformat{\section}{\large\bfseries}{\thesection}{1em}{} % Customize section format here
\titleformat{\subsection}{\large\bfseries\textit}{\thesubsection}{1em}{} % Customize subsection format here
\setcounter{secdepth}{8} % Set maximum depth to 8 (adjust as needed)

% Let's create some content with various levels of hierarchy
\section{Section One}
\subsection{Subsection 1.1}
\subsubsection{Subsubsection 1.1.1}
\subsubsubsection{Subsubsubsection 1.1.1.1}
\subsubsubsection{Subsubsubsection 1.1.1.2}
\ldots
\subsection{Subsection 1.2}
\ldots

\section{Section Two}
\subsection{Subsection 2.1}
\subsubsection{Subsubsection 2.1.1}
\subsubsubsection{Subsubsubsection 2.1.1.1}
\subsubsubsection{Subsubsubsection 2.1.1.2}
\ldots
\subsection{Subsection 2.2}
\ldots

% Generate the table of contents with \tableofcontents command
\tableofcontents

% Begin document content here, after the table of contents
\textbackslash text{Your document content goes here.}
```

This example demonstrates creating a document with eight levels of nested sections (`\section`, `\subsection`, `\subsubsection`, `\subsubsubsection`, `\subsubsubsubsection`, and so on). The `titlesec` package is used to customize the spacing and formatting of the sections and subsections, and the maximum depth is set to eight levels using the `\setcounter{secdepth}` command. The `\tableofcontents` command is placed before the document content to generate the table of contents automatically based on the structure of the document.

