 To create a C++ program that reads a text file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of a specific word, you can use the standard library's `ifstream` for file input and `string` manipulation functions to process lines. Here's an example:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>

int main() {
    // Define the target word and open the input file
    std::string targetWord = "example"; // Set this to your desired word
    std::ifstream file("input.txt"); // Replace "input.txt" with your file name

    int count = 0; // Initialize counter for occurrences
    std::string line; // Holds each line from the file

    // Check if file is open, then process its content line by line
    if (file.is_open()) {
        while (getline(file, line)) {
            size_t pos = line.find(targetWord); // Search for target word in current line
            while (pos != std::string::npos) { // If found, increment counter and search next line from current position
                count++;
                line = line.substr(pos + targetWord.length()); // Remove found word from current line for next search
                pos = line.find(targetWord);
            }
        }
        file.close();
        std::cout << "The word \"" << targetWord << "\" occurs " << count << " times in the file.\n";
    } else {
        std::cerr << "Unable to open file";
    }

    return 0;
}
```

Replace `"example"` with your desired target word and `"input.txt"` with your file name. This program reads the file line by line, searches for the target word using `find()`, and increments the counter when it's found. Note that this approach may have performance issues when dealing with large files or frequent word searches due to repeated substring extraction. For better performance, consider using regular expressions or other text processing libraries if available.
